malware_desc.magic: PE32 executable (console) Intel 80386 (stripped to external PDB), for MS Windows

iocs.description: Registry data was seen being written that appears to specify a script command. This is highly unusual as there are many ways to run scripts and commands provided by Windows operating systems, that are less complicated than using the registry. This technique is commonly seen being used by malware, to hide its presence.
iocs.title: Possible Registry Script Execution

iocs.description: Number of paragraphs in the header. The program's data begins just after the header, and this field can be used to calculate the appropriate file offset. The header includes the relocation entries. A malicious author could alter the value and cause a parser to crash due to memory misalignment.
iocs.title: PE DOS Header Size of the Header in Paragraphs Abnormal

iocs.description: The TimeDateStamp field is usually set to the build date and time of the PE32 File. While this field is set automatically at link or compiler time, it can easily be modified. Malware will often modify or completely remove this field to hinder forensic investigations into the executable.
iocs.title: PE COFF Header Timestamp is Not Set

iocs.description: A domain which is present in a Cisco Umbrella block list was referenced during the analysis of the sample. Cisco Umbrella is a cloud security platform which provides additional detail about network activity such as security and content categorization for domains. Domains in the Cisco Umbrella block list are typically created to be part of a malware campaign and must reach a certain threshold of malicious activity before Cisco Umbrella will add it to the block list.
iocs.title: Domain in Cisco Umbrella Block List

iocs.description: Some malware applications write code into areas of memory intended for data (such as a thread's stack) and then the application executes the malicious code. Windows introduced Data Execution Prevention (DEP) which provided protection against this type of attack. If an attempt to execute code is made in a page that does not have the PAGE_EXECUTE_ protection, an access violation will occur. Malware will often allocate memory in which it will inject code. In order to bypass DEP the allocated memory must be marked Read, Write and Execute. The submitted sample allocated a memory region with the flag PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE. This could indicate the presence of code injection, into itself or a remote process.
iocs.title: Potential Code Injection Detected

iocs.description: Malware will modify executables on a system, to hide logs or other evidence. Also, by modifying various executables it can disable functionality in the system which may detect or hamper the operation of the malware. Lastly, it may be attempting to hide an executable, so that it appears to be a legitimate file. Please review the 'Disk Artifacts' section in order to view additional details about this file.
iocs.title: Process Modified an Executable File

iocs.description: This word contains the absolute value that must be loaded into the SP register before the program is given control. Since the actual stack segment is determined by the loader, and this is merely a value within that segment, it does not need to be relocated. This value can be used by a malicious author to alter the Stack Pointer and access the data that is pointed to by that address.
iocs.title: PE DOS Header Initial SP Value is Abnormal

iocs.description: A COM Class Object Identifier (CLSID) was seen being created and executed. Among their many uses CLSIDs can define behaviour for the program reading them, up to and including what code to execute or what remote host to read download data from. Seeing a CLSID on the command line is rare and is typically limited to system utilities running CLSIDs built into Windows. The fact that a new CLSID was both created and executed is highly suspicious.
iocs.title: CLSID Created And Executed

iocs.description: The TimeDateStamp field is usually set to the build date and time of the PE32 File. While this field is set automatically at link or compiler time, it can easily be modified. Malware will often modify or completely remove this field to hinder forensic investigations into the executable.
iocs.title: PE COFF Header Timestamp is Set to Date Prior to 1999

iocs.description: This word gives the number of entries that exist in the relocation pointer table. It is quite in order for this value to be zero, in which case there are no relocation entries.
iocs.title: PE DOS Header Number of Relocations Was Abnormal

iocs.description: Autorun registry keys can be used to load applications when Windows is started. Malware often uses these key locations to maintain persistence on the host. The values to examine are located in subkeys Run, RunOnce, RunServices, RunServicesOnce, RunOnceEx, or RunOnce\Setup. The key value will indicate where the program that will load on startup is located.
iocs.title: Process Modified Autorun Registry Key Value

iocs.description: Poweliks is a trojan that does not require a file present on the victim's system. Instead, it relies on JavaScript embedded in the registry to store and launch itself. Once launched, the trojan checks for the presence of certain tools, such as PowerShell or .NET and may download them from a Microsoft server if they are not found. It also reaches out to its command and control server for further instructions and to download additional tools or malware. Poweliks first appeared in the summer of 2014.
iocs.title: Poweliks Detected

iocs.description: An excessive number of DNS queries detected. Malware will generally attempt to make contact with its command and control infrastructure when it is first executed. Malware that makes use of domain generation algorithms will often query a large number of domains looking for an active command and control server. In addition, adware and potentially unwanted applications often attempt to resolve a large number of domains.
iocs.title: Excessive Number of DNS Queries

iocs.description: A process modified Internet Explorer's Toolbar Lock setting. When the toolbar is locked users cannot re-position the bars and buttons or make hidden buttons visible. Malware may modify this registry key to prevent users from modifying the toolbar.
iocs.title: Process Locked Internet Explorer's Toolbar

iocs.description: A static analysis rule identified an artifact that has one or more anomalous characteristics. These anomalies may exist due to flaws in the file generation or misunderstandings of the format. Malware may use file anomalies to confuse antivirus parsers and hide code in unusual locations.
iocs.title: Static Analysis Flagged Artifact As Anomalous
